<DOC><DOCNO> AP880426-0260 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-26-88 0011EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   04-26 0503</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0528</SECOND><DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   OPEC and independent oil exporters aregathering for a series of meetings aimed at tightening oil suppliesand boosting prices.   Officials of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countriesand rival oil producers expressed cautious optimism Monday that anagreement could be reached this week on joint measures to supportprices.   ``Any meeting between OPEC and non-OPEC (nations) is important,but this one is particularly so because prices seem to be weak,''said Indonesian delegate Subroto, the nation's former oil minister.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sales of domestically-produced cars and lighttrucks have risen slightly in mid-April from the same period lastyear, according to automakers.   Chrysler Corp. said Monday its daily sales rate rose 21.4percent during the April 11-20 period, while General Motors Corp.reported a 4.4 percent decline and Ford Motor Co. was off 2.6percent.   Sales of all domestically made cars and light trucks totaled353,314 for the eight-day period, up from 308,240 in the nine-dayperiod a year earlier.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sales of existing homes edged up 2.5 percentin March for the second month in a row, a real estate trade groupsays.   The National Association of Realtors said Monday that existingsingle-family homes sold at a seasonally adjusted rate of 3.33million units last month.   The March rise matched a 2.5 percent increase in February, butthe sales rate remained 9.8 percent below March 1987.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   J.P. Stevens andamp; Co. has agreed to be acquired for$1.22 billion by West Point-Pepperell Inc., which plans to splitthe textile giant's assets with a partner and a rival bidder.   Pepperell, which made its bid in conjunction with NTC Group,said Monday it will pay $68.50 in cash for each of Stevens 17.8million outstanding shares under terms of deal forged over theweekend.   West Point, Ga.-based Pepperell will sell $530 million inStevens assets to the New York investment firm Odyssey Partners,its rival in the lengthy takeover battle.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three health groups are asking the governmentto begin regulating low-tar cigarettes on grounds that advertisingclaims for the products make them a drug subject to federaloversight.   If accepted by the Food and Drug Administration, agreed to byCongress and upheld in court, the arguments made by the threegroups on Monday would place the FDA in the ironic position ofregulating cigarettes low in tar and nicotine, but not othercigarettes.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court has let stand an Arizonatelephone company's ban on sexually explicit dial-up messageservices.   In the first ``dial-a-porn'' case to reach the high court, thejustices without comment declined Monday to hear arguments thatMountain Bell's refusal to carry sexually explicit message servicesviolates free-speech rights.   The court's action came a week after Congress sent to PresidentReagan a bill that would ban all dial-a-porn services, which areavailable to callers through ``976'' exchanges and ATandamp;T's ``900''long-distance lines.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>